    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i think it might be a nutrient thing though because it's mostly just the older leaves at the bottom. i'm also worried about the soil being too acidic or something. how do i actually check the ph and what if it's off?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A nutrient issue focused on the older, lower leaves strongly suggests a mobile nutrient deficiency, like nitrogen, which is exactly what you're seeing. You can check your soil pH using a simple home test kit, which are usually inexpensive and come with color charts. If you find the pH is off—say, too acidic or too alkaline—you can adjust it by adding agricultural lime to raise it or elemental sulfur to lower it. It's a slow process, so don't expect instant results, just be patient while you manage the soil chemistry.",
