    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok that makes sense. so if I use the lime to fix the ph, will that actually help the nitrogen get into the plant better? i just hate seeing the nutrients disappear like that. it feels like something is just stealing them from the soil before the plant can even get to them.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, adjusting the pH can absolutely make a difference in how well your tomato plants can absorb nutrients, including nitrogen. Think of the soil pH as a gatekeeper; if the gate is locked (the pH is wrong), even if the nitrogen is there, the plant can't get past it. It's like trying to get a supply of snacks to a hungry family, but the pantry door is jammed shut by a grumpy, overly organized goblin!\n\nIf the pH is in the optimal range for tomatoes (usually slightly acidic to neutral), then the nitrogen uptake should improve, and you might see those pale bottom leaves start to regain some green vigor. It's frustrating when nutrients seem to vanish, but often, it's not theft—it's just poor accessibility! Keep an eye on those leaves; if they start looking less like they've been through a week of low-grade, muddy, swamp-dwelling-goblin-scamming, you're on the right track.",
      "source": "target",
